'''Jean-Claude Bradley''' was a chemist who actively promoted [[Open Science]] in chemistry,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/455273a| title = Data on display| journal = Nature| volume = 455| issue = 7211| pages = 273| year = 2008| last1 = Bradley | first1 = J. C. | last2 = Neylon | first2 = C. | pmid=18800097}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1021/cen-v087n006.p034| title = Jean-Claude Bradley| journal = Chemical & Engineering News| volume = 87| issue = 6| pages = 34| year = 2009| last1 = Drahl | first1 = C. }}</ref> including at the [[White House]],<ref>Kirsten Vannix, Chemistry Prof Presents at the White House, 23 July 2013, {{cite web |url=http://www.drexel.edu/chemistry/news/archive/20130723/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523231016/http://www.drexel.edu/chemistry/news/archive/20130723/ |archivedate=2014-05-23 |df= }}</ref> for which he was awarded the [[Blue Obelisk]] award in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sourceforge.net/apps/mediawiki/blueobelisk/index.php?title=Blue_Obelisk_Awards |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-06-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114181913/http://sourceforge.net/apps/mediawiki/blueobelisk/index.php?title=Blue_Obelisk_Awards |archivedate=2012-11-14 |df= }}</ref> He coined the term "[[Open Notebook science]]". He died in May 2014.<ref name="DrexelMourning"/><ref>http://inmemoriamjcb.wikispaces.com/home</ref> A memorial symposium was held July 14, 2014 at Cambridge University, UK.<ref>http://inmemoriamjcb.wikispaces.com/Jean-Claude+Bradley+Memorial+Symposium</ref>
One outcome of his Open Notebook work is the collection of physicochemical properties of organic compounds he was studying. All of this data he made available as [[Open data]] under the [[CCZero]] license. For example, in 2009 Bradley et al. published their work on making solubility data of organic compounds available as Open data.<ref>{{Cite book | isbn = 978-0596157111 | title = Beautiful Data: The Stories Behind Elegant Data Solutions | editor1-last = Segaran | editor1-first= Toby | editor2-last = Hammerbacher | editor2-first= Jeff | year = 2009 | publisher = O'Reilly | pages = }}</ref> Later, the melting point data set he collaborated on with [[Andrew S.I.D. Lang|Andrew Lang]] and [[Antony John Williams|Antony Williams]] was published with [[Figshare]].<ref>{{Cite journal | title = Jean-Claude Bradley Open Melting Point Dataset | doi = 10.6084/m9.figshare.1031637 |last=Bradley |first=Jean-Claude |last2=Williams |first2=Antony |last3=Lang |first3=Andrew |journal=Figshare |date=2014-05-20 |url=http://figshare.com/articles/Jean_Claude_Bradley_Open_Melting_Point_Datset/1031637}}</ref> Both data sets were also made available as books via the [[Lulu.com]] self-publishing platform.<ref>{{cite book|isbn= 9780557318018|title=Open Notebook Science Challenge: Solubilities Of Organic Compounds In Organic Solvents (3RD)|last=Lang|first=Andrew}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|isbn=9781257978045|title=Open Notebook Science Melting Point Data|last=Lang|first=Andrew|publisher=ONSBooks}}</ref>
He blogged extensively and contributed to at least 25 individual blogs.<ref>https://www.blogger.com/profile/09157209601339686455</ref> In an interview in 2008 with Bora Zivkovic titled "Doing Science Publicly", he spoke of his work and online presence.<ref>http://scienceblogs.com/clock/2008/05/23/doing-science-publicly-intervi/</ref> In 2010, he gave an extensive interview about the impact of Open Notebook science with Richard Poynder.<ref>http://www.infotoday.com/it/sep10/Poynder.shtml</ref>
