'''Sir Noel Stanley Bayliss''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (19 December 1906 – 17 February 1996) was an eminent Australian [[chemist]] and professor of chemistry at the [[University of Western Australia]]. He was a Rhodes Scholar and graduated as dux of the academically renowned [[Melbourne High School (Victoria)|Melbourne High School]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Strong Like Its Pillars|last= Gregory|first= Alan|authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 2005|publisher= Thompson Library Trust|location= [[Melbourne (Victoria)|Melbourne]]|isbn= 0-646-43922-7|page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.asap.unimelb.edu.au/bsparcs/aasmemoirs/bayliss.htm Noel Bayliss Full Biography]</ref> He then attended the [[University of Melbourne]] before going to [[Lincoln College, Oxford]]. The mineral [[baylissite]] K<sub>2</sub>Mg(CO<sub>3</sub>)2•4(H<sub>2</sub>O) is named for him.<ref>http://www.mindat.org/min-583.html</ref>

