{{Infobox scientist |birth_name = Norman Garmezy |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date|1918|6|18|df=y}} |birth_place = [[New York City, New York|New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |residence = | death_date = {{death date and age|2009|11|21|1918|6|18|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]] |citizenship = [[United States|American]] |field = [[Psychology]], [[Developmental Psychology]] |work_institution = [[University of Minnesota]] |alma_mater = [[University of Iowa]] |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = [[Ann Masten]], [[Dante Cicchetti]] |known_for = Risk and Resilience |prizes = [[Institute of Medicine]], [[National Academy of Sciences]] }}
'''Norman Garmezy''' was a university professor of [[psychology]] and pioneer in research on risk and resilience in humans.<ref name="MastenNuechterlein2011">{{cite journal|last1=Masten|first1=Ann S.|last2=Nuechterlein|first2=Keith H.|last3=Wright|first3=Margaret O'Dougherty|title=Norman Garmezy (1918–2009).|journal=American Psychologist|volume=66|issue=2|year=2011|pages=140–141|issn=1935-990X|doi=10.1037/a0021246}}</ref> Garmezy suffered from [[Alzheimer's]] in later life.<ref name="MastenNuechterlein2011" /><ref name= "psy">{{cite journal |last1=Masten |first1=Ann S. |last2=Nuechterlein |first2=Keith H. |last3=Wright |first3=Margaret O'Dougherty |title=Norman Garmezy (1918-2009) |journal=The American Psychologist |date=|volume=66 |issue=2 |pages=140–141 |doi=10.1037/a0021246 |pmid=21299255 |issn=1935-990X}}</ref>
In the field of psychology he focused on risk and resilience in terms of human [[brain]] development.<ref name=psy/>
